I do see this issue in the logs in windriver. What @Ashok found is right, there is a chance that the headers can be duplicated with this code. And To fix it instead of commenting out the whole code, I would check if the header key is present in the map first and if the key is absent I would add the header. This will be a better fix rather than comment the code out, incase if other classes are using it. 
eg
Object headerKey = headers.get(HEADER_AUTHORIZATION);
if (headerKey != null) {
    headers.putIfAbsent(HEADER_AUTHORIZATION, new ArrayList<String>());
      headers.get(HEADER_AUTHORIZATION).add(getBasicAuthenticationCredentials());
}


Also there are unwanted imports which the commit, which needs to be cleaned up.

Thanks @Ashok

Patch Set 1:

@Arul, the code I have commented is the place where headers getting initialized for first time and the method is used only locally. However I see your point to put defensive code but I think that should be there in RestClient.getClientBuilder which is common code. This is the place where Authorization header is getting added again. But this is different project and latest version is different than referred version hence thought of fixing the issue in the first place itself. 
May be we can have the defensive code in https://github.com/onap/aai-rest-client/blob/master/src/main/java/org/onap/aai/restclient/client/RestClient.java -> Line #614 as follows:
      if (clientBuilder.getAuthenticationMode() == RestAuthenticationMode.SSL_BASIC && headers.get(Headers.AUTHORIZATION) == null) {
        builder = builder.header(Headers.AUTHORIZATION,
            clientBuilder.getBasicAuthenticationCredentials());
      }

Meanwhile I have cleaned up unused imports but unable to push the code using "git push origin HEAD:refs/for/master". Please suggest if there is any other way .
